[1] South Korea, 3 new cases, 0 new deaths - MOH 23 Jun 2015
Date: 23 Jun 2015
Source: South Korean MOH 23 Jun 2015
http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=323670


MERS-CoV Daily Update

-Total number of cases now stands at 175: 94 currently receiving treatment (53.7 percent), 54 recovered (30.9 percent), 27 dead (15.4 percent).
-3 additional cases and 4 additional recoveries compared to previous day's numbers; no new fatalities.
-Of the 94 receiving treatment: 78 in stable condition (83.0 percent), 16 reportedly unstable (17.0 percent).
-80 have contracted the virus nosocomially, 62 have come in contact in-facility while visiting family, and 33 are of hospital personnel.

Overview of Confirmed Cases
- The Ministry of Health and Welfare's MERS-CoV Task Force has announced 3 new cases of MERS-CoV - bringing the total tally up to 175 - as of 6 AM KST, 23 Jun 2015.
- The number of total patients currently undergoing treatment has decreased by 1 since yesterday and currently stands at 94 (53.7 percent of total); 4 have recovered, bringing the number up to 54 (30.9 percent); the fatality count currently stands at 27 (15.4 percent).

New Cases
- 3 additional cases have been confirmed since yesterday.
- Patient no. 173 (70 year old female) was a caregiver visiting a patient at Kyung Hee University Medical Center ED during Patient no. 76's hospitalization at the aforementioned institution.
- Patient no. 174 (75 year old male) was hospitalized at Seoul Samsung Medical Center ED on 4 Jun 2015, 8 Jun 2015, and 9 Jun 2015 at Seoul Samsung Medical Center;
- Patient no. 175 (74 year old male) was revealed to be a family member of Patient no. 118, who came in contact with the virus at Pyeongtaek Good Morning Hospital. Details regarding the medical history of Patients no. 174 and 175 soon to follow.

New Recoveries
- Patients no. 14 (35 year old male, 35), 69 (57 year old male), 109 (39 year old female), and 116 (56 year old female) have all been discharged in between 21 Jun 2015 and the morning of 22 Jun 2015, bringing the total number of recoveries to 54.
- Dischargees underwent various courses of symptomatic treatments, such as antibiotic and anti-viral treatment. The patients were cleared for discharge after signs of respiratory distress and fever subsided, and confirmatory tests resulted negative.
- Of the 54 total recoveries, 30 (55.6 percent) are male with 24 (44.4 percent) being female; 14 have been in the 40s (25.9 percent), 11 each have been in the 50s (20.4 percent each), 9 have been in the 60s (16.7 percent), 8 have been in the 30s (14.8 percent), with 7 patients having been in the 70s (13.0 percent).

New Fatalities
- There are no new fatalities to report.
- Of the 27 reported fatalities to date, 20 have been male (74.1 percent), while 7 have been female (25.9 percent); in terms of age distribution, the lion's share of the fatalities have been in the 60s with 9 (33.3 percent) fatalities, followed by 8 (29.6 percent) fatalities in the 70s, 5 (18.5 percent) in the 80s, 4 (14.8 percent) in the 50s and 1 (3.7 percent) in the 40s.
- 25 of the 27 fatalities (92 percent) were elderly, immunocompromised, and/or suffering from pre-existing conditions such as COPD, cancer, cerebrovascular disease, and diabetes.

Modes of Transmission and Demographic Characteristics
- A categorical analysis on the modes of transmission of the 175 total cases reveals:
- Nosocomial infection is the most common mode of transmission at 45.7 percent (80 cases), infections as a result of hospital visits by family members comprise 35.4 percent of total cases (62), while infections of faculty and other medical personnel is report to be at 18.9 percent (33)

- Male infectees comprise 61.1 percent of the total cases (107), and females, 38.9 percent (68)
- Total distribution by age of all cases is as follows: 36 patients (20.6 percent) are in the 50s, 35 (20 percent) are in their 60s, 31 are in their 40s (17.1 percent), 30 are in their 70s (17.1 percent), while 26 are in their 30s (14.9 percent).

Isolations and Quarantine
- As of 23 Jun 2015 6 AM KST, 2805 are under quarantine with the reflected numbers being 26.8 percent lower than previous day's numbers (a decrease of 1028); the total number of those released from quarantine has increased to 10 718, which equates to an increase of 1378 compared to previous day's [22 Jun 2015] numbers.
- Of the 2805 under quarantine, 2091 are under home isolation (a 31.4 percent decrease, or a decrease of 957), while the number of hospital quarantines has decreased by 71 (9 percent), bringing the total number of hospital quarantines to 714.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The total number of cases with confirmed MERS-CoV infection is now up to 175 including 27 deaths with a reported case fatality rate of 15.4 percent. Of the 3 newly confirmed cases, 2 are most likely 4th generation cases. The 3rd case is not clear as the dates of exposure to the Samsung emergency room do not correspond with the earlier dates when case #14 was in the emergency room. While there are cases continuing to be confirmed, they are at a much slower pace than earlier, and dates of contact seem to be in the 1st week of June, suggesting that transmission is slowing down. According to a media report, 2 of the 3 newly confirmed cases were individuals who were in isolation as suspected cases preceding the confirmation of MERS-CoV infection (see http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/business/2015/06/23/21/0504000000AEN20150623001700320F.html).

Noteworthy is that one of the recovered cases announced today is case #14 - one of the "superspreaders".

The total number of individuals who have been or are being followed by the MOH in quarantine is indicative of a massive effort on the part of the MOH - 2805 currently under quarantine and 10 718 released following 14 days of quarantine.

The HealthMap/ProMED map of South Korea can be found at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3457227,195. - Mod.MPP]

