[3] Middle East Regional Update 2015 - WHO EMRO
Date: 22 Jun 2015
Source: WHO EMRO (Eastern Mediterranean Regional Office) Situation update [edited]
http://www.emro.who.int/health-topics/mers-cov/news.html


MERS-CoV - Regional situation update as of 15 Jun 2015
Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) in the Eastern Mediterranean Region: situation update
---------------------------------------
A total of 212 laboratory-confirmed cases of Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) including 95 deaths (CFR: 44.8 percent) were reported from the countries of the WHO Eastern Mediterranean Region between [1 Jan 2015 to 15 Jun 2015]. The majority of the cases were reported from Saudi Arabia (201 cases) followed by the United Arab Emirates (4 cases), Qatar (3 cases), Oman (3 cases), and the Islamic Republic of Iran (1 case).

Compared to 2014, there has not been any substantial increase in numbers of reported cases, and the epidemiological characteristics of the cases reported in 2015 do not show any significant difference when compared with cases reported during the same period in 2013 and in 2014.

Males and the median age group of 50-59 years continue to be at the highest risk for acquiring infection.

Compared to 2014, although the cases have not registered a significant increase, small sized hospital outbreaks continue to be reported from Saudi Arabia and remain a major concern. Since epidemiological week no. 16 [week of 19-25 Apr 2015, consistent with the presumed start date of 20 Apr 2015 - Mod.MPP], a nosocomial outbreak involving 2 hospitals in Hofuf city of Al-Ahsa of Eastern Province has been reported. A total of 31 laboratory-confirmed cases of MERS-CoV including 14 deaths (CFR: 45.1 percent) were reported from this outbreak. The date of symptom onset of the last case reported from this outbreak was [2 Jun 2015].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In looking at the data for the region, one is struck by the reported case fatality rate of 44.8 percent when compared with the overall case fatality rate reported by WHO of 35.4 percent (see MERS-CoV (73): South Korea, Saudi Arabia, Thailand, WHO, RFI 20150620.3453094). One can't help but wonder how many milder cases are being missed and attributed to other febrile respiratory diseases, so that it's the severe respiratory diseases that are tested for the MERS-CoV.

This update provides the 1st official data on the ongoing hospital based outbreak in Hufoof. According the information above, the outbreak began the week of 20 Apr 2015 and involves 2 hospitals. Reviewing specific information on individual cases, the case that occurred on 20 Apr 2015 (the "index case") of the hospital-based outbreak had a history of frequent exposure to camels and sheep. As of 22 Jun 2015, there have been a total of 38 cases reported from Hufoof since 20 Apr 2015, including 18 deaths (reported case fatality rate of 47.4 percent).

The HealthMap/ProMED map of Saudi Arabia and neighboring countries can be found at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3457227,131. - Mod.MPP]

